21 [31]. Ablative Absolute. The following uses are characteristic:

(a) the neuter ablative singular of the participle stands by itself : multum certat0, xi 10, 3 ; nec ultra expectato quarn, xi 26, 7 ; this often introduces a substantival clause: non distincto sua an aliena manu (perisset), xi 38, 2 ; comperto Graecam quoque litterar turam non simul coeptam absolutamque, xi 13, 3 ;

(b) the participle is used without any word in agreement, where it can easily be supplied from the sense of the passage: conce- dente (eo), vi 16, 5 ; invalido (imperatore), vi 47, 43

(c) the participle is followed by a relative, without expression of the antecedent: additis quae ante deliquerant, vi 9, 1 ; missis qui . . . pellicerent, xi 19, 3; excitis quorum de sententia petitus rex, xii 12, 3.
